cp
You can copy a file using the cp command:

Bash
touch test
cp apple another_apple
(Note: The slide syntax example has a slight typo where it runs touch test but then copies a file named apple instead).

To copy folders you need to add the -r option to recursively copy the whole folder contents:

Bash
mkdir fruits
cp -r fruits cars
💡 Clarification on How cp -r Works
Just like rm -r, the -r flag here stands for recursive.

When copying directories with cp -r source_folder target_folder, the behavior depends on whether the target exists:

If cars does not exist: The system creates a new folder named cars and copies all files/folders from inside fruits directly into it.

If cars already exists: The system copies the entire fruits folder inside the cars directory, resulting in the path cars/fruits/.